  "text": "The Firefox content process lifecycle in the multi-process (Fission) architecture is managed by several key C++ classes in the dom/ipc/ directory:\n\n1. **ContentParent** (dom/ipc/ContentParent.h/.cpp): The parent-side content process manager that represents a single content process. This class inherits from PContentParent and handles IPC communication with the child process, manages the lifetime of the process, and coordinates with other Firefox components.\n\n2. **ContentProcessManager** (dom/ipc/ContentProcessManager.h/.cpp): A singleton registry that maintains mappings of all active content processes (ContentParent instances) and their associated tabs (BrowserParent instances). It provides lookup methods to retrieve processes by ID and to register/unregister remote frames.\n\n3. **BrowserParent** (dom/ipc/BrowserParent.h/.cpp): The parent-side representation of a tab/browser element. It implements the PBrowserParent protocol and handles tab-specific IPC communication, input events, and rendering. Each BrowserParent is associated with a ContentParent that manages the underlying process.\n\n4. **PreallocatedProcessManager** (dom/ipc/PreallocatedProcessManager.h/.cpp): Manages a pool of pre-allocated content processes to improve responsiveness. The public class PreallocatedProcessManager provides static methods, while PreallocatedProcessManagerImpl (defined in the .cpp file) is the actual singleton implementation that observes system events and prefs to maintain the pool.\n\nThese classes work together to implement Firefox's Fission architecture: ContentParent manages individual processes, ContentProcessManager provides a global registry for process lookup, BrowserParent represents individual tabs within those processes, and PreallocatedProcessManager optimizes process creation by pre-warming processes when available."
}

